FAQ - PLEASE READ! I am not going to respond to questions that are covered here!

Q. I am interested in your gun. Is it still available?
A. If you see this ad, most likely. The firearms are reserved for pickup on my web site, by making an appointment to buy. Someone could be doing it right now, and first person to reserve the firearm wins. Go to www.preciseshooter.com -> FAQ -> How to buy, read the requirements, and make the appointment on the site. If someone has made it just before you, I will notify you within a short time (usually, an hour), otherwise - see you shortly.

PLEASE DO NOT ASK WHETHER THE GUN IS STILL AVAILABLE! I WILL NOT RESPOND.

Q. How do I buy?
A. This is a dealer listing, NICS check, taxes, etc are all required. Please go to www.preciseshooter.com -> FAQ -> How to buy, read the requirements, and make the appointment to pick up.

Q. I am interested in your gun. Call me @ xxx-xxx-xxxx
A. Excellent. Go to www.preciseshooter.com -> FAQ -> How to buy, read the requirements, and make the appointment to pick it up.

Q. Are there any other fees, in addition to the price and taxes? NICS, background check, etc?
A. No.

Q. What is the tax rate?
A. 9.5%

Q. Where are you located?
A. Queen Anne neighborhood in Seattle.

Q. Can we meet in Burien on Monday morning?
A. No, FFL requirements are that the transfers happen at a licensed location. Also, the only times you can come over are the appointments that you can reserve on the site. No other time slots are available.

Q. I see you carry Savage rifles. Can you find me MKII FV-SR?
A. No. Please see here for what I can or cannot do: http://www.preciseshooter.com/NotInStock.aspx

Q. Do you take trades?
A. Sometimes. However:
a) firearms only,
b) they need to be our of current production (I can get new ones at wholesale prices), or you have to offer them to me at well below wholesale
c) I do not resell the trades, so they should fit my personal interests (which only include military as well as highly accurate, competition guns - no self defense guns like Glocks, M&Ps, XD*, and the like)
d) the exchange rate should be fair (see here for more: http://www.preciseshooter.com/blog/PriceGuide.aspx

Q. Is the price firm? Will you take XXX (70% of the asking price)?
A. The price is firm.

Q. Can you help me mount a scope/replace a trigger/fix a feeding problem?
A. Sorry, I do not do gunsmithing.

Q. Will you ship?
A. Yes - go to www.preciseshooter.com -> How to buy and read the section for buying outside Seattle area. Insured shipping via Fedex on this one will be $30.

title: For Sale/Trade:  1934 izzy m91/30
postcontent:
Nagants in good enough shape to be salvaged were part of the soviets massive refurbishment program following ww2. The primary reasons behind the huge post war overhaul of large, obsolete rifle stockpiles were the anticipation of another impending world war, and the plan to call up seasoned veterans in defense of the motherland. Already familiar with their old mosin nagant rifles and revolvers, those veterans would likely have required very little new training and would easily and rapidly reintegrate into the red machine. 
With the development of newer semi auots that would have required extensive massive retraining, the important issue became of quick mobilization became apearant. However time passed and those great ww2 veterans eventually aged beyond the point of viability. While newer weapons took over the worlds battlefields, the stocks of long outdated ordnance were now imported to the USA. 

This is a pre war 1934 izzy manufacture m90/31 with hexagonal reciever with original russian laminate non refurbished stock. This rifles bore is stone mint shiny chromed out! "Have neer seen one like this" the weapon bears No refurbishment marks or other countrys arsenal markings! The metal has not a mark on it is stone mint! The magazine follower, action etc have no wear! Mint bore. All matching. No refurbishment marks from other countrys !!
This is a very early import that was sold wrapped in brown paper tied in twine. This rifle saw little to no action its entire life, maybe an officers or political gaurds weapon

The rifles antiquated lines, and historical signifigance is something to be sought after for years to come. This rifle was made well when an individuals workmanship was apreciated and one took pride in what they did. It also was a matter of national pride, a "we made it here" battle rifle.

title: For Sale:  1911 grips, Gobs of
postcontent:
I have four pairs of grips for your favorite slabby Gov gun. A pair for every taste and pocketbook!

In the first photo, on the left, you see an lovely pair in tasteful brown plastic. WWII sty-lee. These came from one of those Norinco 1911's from way back when that were made out of 5140 and chewed up all those milling cutters of gunsmits trying to open up the sight dovetails so that when you mentioned that you had one and how good it was for the money compared to that dismal colt 1991 a1 they would get one of those old fashioned looks on their faces and say "Oh... one o them Chy-Nee guns, huh? We don't touch em."  $5 beautiful dollars.

Next to that is a toothsome pair in walnut with checkering and flowery scroolly flourishes fit for the finest fourth of july, fourtyfive slugfest or Cinco de mayo singalong.
$6 dinars.

The second picture has a pair of black rubber Pachmayr slabs with steely liners for sweaty hands and cheap bulk reloads. $10

The last pair are the checkered walnut well worn ones and I hesitate to even offer them up but what else am I gonna do, smoke them? Now bear with me. Many years ago I bought a very early Colt 1911 in 38 super from an old fellow at the hospital I worked at while in college. It was an all original un monkeyed with 02xx serial number in about 85% condition and worth many times what I payed for it. I was poor, I was hungry, I loved a motorcycle, and I couldnt resist that stack of 100 dollar bills. I sold it to a philistine who brought a new pair of fancy figured wood grips with him when he bought it. He changed them right there at the kitchen table of my apartment and left the old ones behind. He said they werent befitting an "Investment Grade" firearm and he was out the door. So, here they are still. $20 I dont know how to prove their pedigree or if anyone even cares. I'm ambivalent. I dont believe in collector guns, or garage queens, or trophy wives. If you have an old Gov model that needs period grips I'd probably just give em to you. 

Lee at 479871764four.

Oh yeah, that odd grip at the bottom of the first photo is some indian hardwood left when I broke the other one off due to a stuck screw and stripped escution. It's a right panel. free.

And the way the pachmayrs look way small is some artifact of the light, angle and majic. It's really normal size.

title: For Sale/Trade:  MGI Hydra 5.56 with 7.62x39 conversion and ammo
postcontent:
I have to sell some toys to cover expenses...So up for sale is my New Mk15 Hydra by MGI industries. These unique AR15 clones have a proprietary switch barrel system that requires no tools. under the monolithic rail is a slide lock. release the lock slide it forward to expose 2 cam levers. Swing the cam levers out to 90 degrees and pull the barrel and gas tube free of the receiver. Change the bolt or simply have a new carrier/bolt set up ready, install and done. Can be achieved in seconds. 
The truly unique part of the MGI Hydra is the lower receiver. The problem with multi cal AR15s always revolves around the magazine well. 7.62x39 ar15 magazines are renowned for their unreliability, Pistol calibers for their finicky magazine blocks, and limitations of calibers by the size of the mag well. MGI fixed that in this design. The magazine well slide into and locks on machined rails in the receiver. Yes...the magazine well is removable. The magazine wells take the ammunition's native magazine. The 7.62x39 takes AK mags, 9mm takes glock mags with no block needed. Everything from .22lr to .50 beouwulf is already available. Conversion Kits can be ordered directly from MGI and come with magazine well barrel and bolt specific to the caliber and the mag well specific to magazine used. They are also the only ones offering a .308/762x51 conversion in an AR15 (not AR10 frame) by using their mag well and magazine.....why have to carry several rifles or have to keep several on hand. One AR can do it all. Saves space and carry loads.
Comes with over sized pistol case that holds upper lower and 2 barrels Plus ammo can with mags and ammo.
Im Selling the A Mk15 Hydra with the 223/5.56 Base with 6 position collapsible stock
comes with:
Modular Hydra lower with easy pull take down pins
Lower can be set up for any caliber .22 to .458 socom..even .308 in this lower.

223/5.56 barrel 
AR15 mag well
Removable Carry Handle Sight
Easy pull take down pins on 5.56 mag well and lower

380 rounds of mixed 223 ammo

7.62x39 barrel 
7.62x39 bolt

approx 400 rounds mixed 7.62x39 ammunition
